A) Turing Test (chat-based)

Goal: a human judge chats with two “participants” (one human, one AI) without knowing which is which. After the chat, the judge guesses who is AI.

Architecture

Client/UI (browser)

Judge chat screen

Participant chat screen

Server (API + session manager)

Creates “rooms” (sessions)

Assigns roles (judge / participant A / participant B)

Relays messages in real time (simple polling) or WebSockets

AI Agent service

Given conversation context, generates replies

Evaluation module

After session ends: collects judge guess + chat logs

Computes metrics: judge accuracy, time taken, message count, etc.

Storage

In-memory for demo

Real life: DB (Postgres) + Redis for sessions

Logging

Store chat transcript + timestamps

Flow

Judge starts a session

Server creates two participants: A and B

One is a real human, the other is the AI agent (hidden)

Judge chats → server routes messages

End → judge chooses who is AI

Evaluation stores transcript + result

B) CAPTCHA (image/text challenge)

Goal: stop bots from submitting forms.

Architecture

CAPTCHA Generator

Creates challenge (random text / math / image distortion)

Produces captcha_id + answer hash

CAPTCHA Store

Store {captcha_id: answer_hash, expiry_time, attempts}

Real life: Redis with TTL

Verification API

Receives captcha_id + user_answer

Checks hash match + expiration + attempts

Rate limiter

Limits requests per IP/user

Integration point

Any protected endpoint checks CAPTCHA token before processing

Flow

Client requests /captcha/new

Server returns captcha image/text + captcha_id

Client submits form with captcha_id + answer

Server verifies → allow/bloc
